Thought for 1m 42s

Yes. Here’s the clean diagnosis I’d give Claude.

The issue looks like two layers stacked together:

Real bug in the event service poller
The Scylla event-bus cursor can skip past the current minute when a bucket is empty, which makes later events in that same minute permanently invisible. Your pasted note explains the race clearly: an empty poll at 08:35 advances the cursor to 08:36, then an event written at 08:35:00.100 is now behind the cursor and never read.
Quickstart image can easily run stale binaries
The quickstart Dockerfile copies binaries from a local binaries/ directory into the image, and in the tarball I checked that directory is not populated. So if Claude patched source but did not rebuild the host binaries and re-run the quickstart image build, the containers will still run old code. That is the classic cardboard dragon: brave patch, same old binary inside the cage.

Send Claude this:

Claude, here is the actual issue and the required fix path. Do these exact steps.

1. Fix the Scylla cursor race in scylla_bus.go

In pollOnce(), the catch-up logic for len(events) == 0 must not advance past the current minute bucket.

Replace the old logic:

advanced := t.Add(time.Minute)
if advanced.After(sb.lastSeq.Time()) {
    sb.lastSeq = gocql.MinTimeUUID(advanced)
}

with:

advanced := t.Add(time.Minute)
nowBucket := time.Now().UTC().Truncate(time.Minute)

// Only skip buckets that are fully in the past.
// Never skip the current minute because writes may still arrive there.
if advanced.Before(nowBucket) && advanced.After(sb.lastSeq.Time()) {
    sb.lastSeq = gocql.MinTimeUUID(advanced)
}
2. Verify the semantics carefully

The invariant is:

empty past bucket → safe to skip
empty current bucket → do not skip
current minute is still open for writes

That is the whole bug. The event is durably stored, but the poller jumps over it.

3. Rebuild the actual binaries used by quickstart

This part is crucial. Patching source alone is not enough.

The quickstart image uses binaries copied into Docker from the local host build output. So after patching the event service, rebuild the host binaries first, then repopulate quickstart binaries/, then rebuild the image.

The sequence should be:

# rebuild host binaries from the real source tree
# use your normal build command here
# example placeholder:
make build
# or whatever produces /usr/lib/globular/bin/event_server etc.

# then from globular-quickstart
make collect
make build
docker compose up -d --force-recreate

If he skips make collect and make build, the containers keep using old binaries.

4. Prove the container is running the patched binary

After rebuild, verify from inside the running event service container or image:

strings /usr/lib/globular/bin/event_server | grep -E "maxBucketsPerPoll|maxEventsPerPoll|event-publisher|QueryEvents"

Or more directly, inspect the patched source commit/build metadata if available.

The goal is not “source was edited”.
The goal is “the container binary changed”.

5. Add a regression test

Create a test for this exact race:

set cursor at start of current minute bucket
poll returns zero events
write one event into same current minute
next poll must still see it

Pseudo-shape:

func TestPollDoesNotAdvancePastCurrentBucket(t *testing.T) {
    // arrange: lastSeq at current minute start
    // arrange: first scan of current bucket returns zero rows
    // act: pollOnce()
    // assert: lastSeq did not move to next minute

    // then insert event in same bucket with seq > original lastSeq
    // act: pollOnce()
    // assert: event is returned / delivered
}
6. If scenario tests still fail after that

Then the next suspect is not the race anymore, but stale quickstart content. Check:

binaries/event_server timestamp/hash before image build
image rebuild actually happened
container binary hash matches rebuilt host binary

Useful commands:

sha256sum binaries/event_server
docker run --rm globulario/globular-node:latest sha256sum /usr/lib/globular/bin/event_server

Those hashes should match.

My own read: the code bug is real, but the quickstart stale-binary problem is very likely why Claude can patch and still see the same failure. One bug is in logic, the other is in the test harness supply chain. Two locked doors, one keyring.

If you want, I can also draft the exact commit message and a tiny regression test skeleton for Claude.